<page id="26" bbox="0.000,0.000,612.000,792.000" rotate="0"><Artifact Attached="[/Top]" Subtype="/Header" Type="/Pagination">PEOPLE’S REPUBLIC OF CHINA—MACAO SAR </Artifact><Artifact Attached="[/Bottom]" Subtype="/Footer" Type="/Pagination">INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND 21 </Artifact><P MCID="0">Figure 1. Real Sector </P><P MCID="1"></P><P MCID="2">Growth slumped in 2015 due to a sharp contraction in tourism exports… </P><P MCID="3"> </P><P MCID="4">…thus far, this has primarily manifested itself in a fall in casino profits… </P><P MCID="5"></P><P MCID="6"> </P><P MCID="7"> </P><P MCID="8"> </P><P MCID="9"></P><P MCID="10">…and a material correction in housing prices. </P><P MCID="11"> </P><P MCID="12">Inflation more broadly also moderated. </P><P MCID="13"></P><P MCID="14"> </P><P MCID="15"> </P><P MCID="16"> </P><P MCID="17"></P><P MCID="18">However, unemployment remains near historical lows and median wages are still up significantly in recent years. </P><P MCID="19"> </P><P MCID="20">Moreover, Q3 seasonally adjusted GDP shows nascent signs of a return to positive growth. </P><P MCID="21"></P><P MCID="22"> </P><P MCID="23"> </P><P MCID="24"> </P><P MCID="25"></P><P MCID="26">Sources: CEIC Data Company Ltd.; Haver Analytics; and IMF staff calculations. </P><P MCID="27"></P><P MCID="28">5070901101302009Q12009Q42010Q32011Q22012Q12012Q42013Q32014Q22015Q12015Q42016Q3Real GDP (In billion of MOP, Seasonally adjusted)</P><P MCID="29">020406080100120Mar-07Sep-07Mar-08Sep-08Mar-09Sep-09Mar-10Sep-10Mar-11Sep-11Mar-12Sep-12Mar-13Sep-13Mar-14Sep-14Mar-15Sep-15Mar-16Sep-16ResidentialIndustrialOfficeHousing Prices(Average price Index, June 2014=100)</P><P MCID="30">01234567Jan-10Feb-11Apr-12Jun-13Jul-14Sep-15Nov-16Inflation(In percent, year-on-year growth)</P><P MCID="31">-25-1052035200020032006200920122015ConsumptionInvestmentNet exports: goodsNet exports: servicesReal GDP growth (in percent)Real GDP: Contribution to Growth(In percentage points)Sources: CEIC; and IMF staff calculations.</P><P MCID="32">0100200300400200420052006200720082009201020112012201320142015Gaming Sector(In billion of MOP)ProfitsReceiptsExpenditure</P><P MCID="33">1.522.533.548000100001200014000160002009Q12009Q42010Q32011Q22012Q12012Q42013Q32014Q22015Q12015Q42016Q3Labor MarketMedian wage (MOP)Unemployment rate (In percent, RHS)</P></page>
<page id="27" bbox="0.000,0.000,612.000,792.000" rotate="0"><Artifact Attached="[/Top]" Subtype="/Header" Type="/Pagination">PEOPLE’S REPUBLIC OF CHINA—MACAO SAR </Artifact><Artifact Attached="[/Bottom]" Subtype="/Footer" Type="/Pagination">22 INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND </Artifact><P MCID="0">Figure 2. External Developments </P><P MCID="1"></P><P MCID="2">Large private profits and fiscal surpluses have led to substantial national savings. </P><P MCID="3"> </P><P MCID="4">Given also limited domestic investment opportunities, Macao SAR regularly has large current account surpluses. </P><P MCID="5"></P><P MCID="6"> </P><P MCID="7"> </P><P MCID="8"> </P><P MCID="9"></P><P MCID="10">As a result, Macao SAR is now a large net foreign creditor... </P><P MCID="11"> </P><P MCID="12">…and reserves remain ample even after the large transfer to the fiscal reserve fund in 2012. </P><P MCID="13"></P><P MCID="14"> </P><P MCID="15"> </P><P MCID="16"> </P><P MCID="17"></P><P MCID="18">Going forward, export competitiveness could be vulnerable if there is a further depreciation in the RMB… </P><P MCID="19"> </P><P MCID="20">…as two-thirds of tourists are from Mainland China. </P><P MCID="21"></P><P MCID="22"> </P><P MCID="23"> </P><P MCID="24"> </P><P MCID="25"></P><P MCID="26">Sources: CEIC Data Company Ltd.; Haver Analytics; and IMF staff calculations. </P><P MCID="27"></P><P MCID="28"> </P><P MCID="29"> </P><P MCID="30">0102030405060201020112012201320142015Public savingsPrivate savingsNational Savings(In percent of GDP)</P><P MCID="31">-25-15-55152520022003200420052006200720082009201020112012201320142015Current account balanceReserve assetsCapital and financial balance plus errorsBalance of Payments(In billion of US dollars)</P><P MCID="32">010020030040050060020022003200420052006200720082009201020112012201320142015Foreign AssetsForeign LiabilitiesNet Foreign AssetsEstimated International Investment Position(In percent of GDP)Sources: Haver, Staff Estimates</P><P MCID="33">050100150