<page id="28" bbox="0.000,0.000,612.000,792.000" rotate="0"><Artifact Attached="[/Top]" Subtype="/Header" Type="/Pagination">PEOPLE’S REPUBLIC OF CHINA—MACAO SAR </Artifact><Artifact Attached="[/Bottom]" Subtype="/Footer" Type="/Pagination">INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND 23 </Artifact><P MCID="0">Figure 3. Banking Sector Developments </P><P MCID="1"></P><P MCID="2">Amid the recent downturn, credit to the private sector has decelerated sharply… </P><P MCID="3"> </P><P MCID="4">…but asset quality has remained high with extremely low NPLs… </P><P MCID="5"></P><P MCID="6"> </P><P MCID="7"> </P><P MCID="8"> </P><P MCID="9"></P><P MCID="10">…and no sign of a hit to profits. </P><P MCID="11"> </P><P MCID="12">There has been some contraction in banks domestic and external funding… </P><P MCID="13"></P><P MCID="14"> </P><P MCID="15"> </P><P MCID="16"> </P><P MCID="17"></P><P MCID="18">…but liquidity is robust amid a high deposit-loan ratio and ample liquid assets. </P><P MCID="19"> </P><P MCID="20">Going forward, a key supervisory challenge will be monitoring the banking system’s external portfolios, which are large relative to GDP. </P><P MCID="21"></P><P MCID="22"> </P><P MCID="23"> </P><P MCID="24"> </P><P MCID="25"></P><P MCID="26">Sources: CEIC Data Company Ltd.; Haver Analytics; and IMF staff calculations. </P><P MCID="27"></P><P MCID="28">0.60.811.21.41.6201120122013201420152016Q2MacaoHong KongBanking Sector: Return on Assets(In percent)</P><P MCID="29">09182736452011Q12011Q32012Q12012Q32013Q12013Q32014Q12014Q32015Q12015Q32016Q12016Q3Domestic Loans to Private Sector(In percent, year-on-year growth)</P><P MCID="30">-2002040602011Q12011Q32012Q12012Q32013Q12013Q32014Q12014Q32015Q12015Q32016Q12016Q3Foreign liabilitiesResident depositsBanking Sector: Resident Deposits and Foreign Liabilities(In percent, year-on-year growth)</P><P MCID="31">30354045501101201301401502010Q12011Q22012Q32013Q42015Q12016Q2Customer deposits to non-interbank loansLiquid assets to total asset (RHS)Bank Liquidity(In percent)</P><P MCID="32">-400-300-200-1000100200300400200520062007200820092010201120122013201420152016Domestic AssetsForeign AssetsDomestic LiabilitiesForeign LiabilitesBank Balance Sheets(In percent of GDP)Sources: Haver Analytics; and IMF staff estimates</P><P MCID="33">0.00.10.20.30.40.52011Q12011Q42012Q32013Q22014Q12014Q42015Q32016Q2Bank Asset Quality: Non-Performing Loans(In percent of total loans)</P></page>
<page id="29" bbox="0.000,0.000,612.000,792.000" rotate="0"><Artifact Attached="[/Top]" Subtype="/Header" Type="/Pagination">PEOPLE’S REPUBLIC OF CHINA—MACAO SAR </Artifact><Artifact Attached="[/Bottom]" Subtype="/Footer" Type="/Pagination">24 INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND </Artifact><P MCID="0">Figure 4. Fiscal Developments </P><P MCID="1"></P><P MCID="2">While remaining in surplus, the general government fiscal balance has declined sharply… </P><P MCID="3"> </P><P MCID="4">…due primarily to a sharp fall in gaming revenue. </P><P MCID="5"></P><P MCID="6"> </P><P MCID="7"> </P><P MCID="8"> </P><P MCID="9"></P><P MCID="10">However, general government expenditures have also risen faster than GDP due primarily to investment and social benefits. </P><P MCID="11"> </P><P MCID="12">Macao SAR does have ample fiscal space given zero public debt and a substantial stock of fiscal reserves… </P><P MCID="13"></P><P MCID="14"> </P><P MCID="15"> </P><P MCID="16"> </P><P MCID="17"></P><P MCID="18">…but a sharp rise in aging will weigh on pension obligations in the future… </P><P MCID="19"> </P><P MCID="20">…and public investment may need to rise to address tourism bottlenecks. </P><P MCID="21"></P><P MCID="22"> </P><P MCID="23"> </P><P MCID="24"> </P><P MCID="25"></P><P MCID="26">Sources: CEIC Data Company Ltd.; Financial Services Bureau; United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2015). World Population Prospects: The 2015 Revision, DVD Edition;.and IMF staff calculations. </P><P MCID="27"></P><P MCID="28"> </P><P MCID="29">102030402010201120122013201420152016BudgetBudgetary central government revenueGaming tax revenue (RHS)Government Revenue and Gaming Tax Revenue(In percent of GDP)</P><P MCID="30">0510152025302010201120122013201420152016BudgetGeneral Government Balance(In percent of GDP)</P><P MCID="31">05101520252010201120122013201420152016BudgetWagesGoods and servicesSubsidiesSocial benefitsOther current expenditureCapital expenditureGeneral